                            <Heading/>
                            <Paragraph>Article III of the Constitution declares, in section 1, that
                                the judicial power of the United States shall be invested in one
                                Supreme Court and in "such inferior Courts as the Congress may from
                                time to time ordain and establish." The Supreme Court has held that
                                these constitutional courts ". . . share in the exercise of the
                                judicial power defined in that section, can be invested with no
                                other jurisdiction, and have judges who hold office during good
                                behavior, with no power in Congress to provide
                                otherwise."</Paragraph>
                        </Detail>
